Right now the shape I see is:

1. Python → C conversion first
That is the right foundation if Beast2 is meant to feel fast, durable, and local-first. It also matches your DSL direction: simple enough to parse in C, transparent enough to stay understandable, and closer to "command resolves to execution" than "prompt disappears into a black box."  ￼  ￼

2. Image gen first
Also right. Image generation is the best beachhead because it gives you visible artifacts quickly, lets you prove the generator/artifact/archive model, and keeps the system grounded in something users can immediately feel. That lines up with Beast2’s original strength as a generator-centered environment rather than a pile of disconnected outputs.  ￼  ￼

3. Beast Academy after that
Strong move. Once image gen exists in C well enough to demonstrate the architecture, docs stop being "extra" and become part of the product. Your own philosophy already points there: the manual should be living, not separate from the system. Academy can become both onboarding and the first serious test of Beast as a language interface for teaching.  ￼  ￼

4. Beast language next, with UI at least partly in Beast language
This feels like the real hinge. Once the UI is partly expressed in Beast language, the product starts becoming itself. That is where Beast stops being "a desktop app with AI features" and starts becoming a command-and-creation system whose interface is language-backed all the way down. Your Beast3 and interface-language docs clearly point in that direction already.  ￼  ￼

5. iOS after those
That priority also tracks. iOS makes most sense once the command model, docs, and language layer are solid, because the phone version should probably not be a full clone of the desktop UI. It should be a command console, artifact browser, academy reader, and remote control surface first. If you do iOS too early, you risk building UI twice before the language layer is mature.

My honest read: this is a good order, but the highest-risk boundary is between docs and language. Beast Academy should not become a side project or static documentation pile. It should be written so it directly feeds the Beast language effort. In other words: every important Academy concept should be phrased the way the system itself will eventually speak.

So the clean version of your roadmap looks like this:

engine → generator → academy → language → iOS

And under that:

C runtime → image artifacts → living manual → language UI primitives → mobile command surface

That feels coherent.

The main thing I would guard against is letting iOS become "a second frontend." It should probably be framed more narrowly at first:
a Beast terminal, Beast Academy reader, artifact viewer, and simple remote execution surface. That would preserve momentum and avoid dragging the whole desktop UI problem onto a phone too early.

You’ve got a very believable progression here. It feels like Beast2 becoming more executable, and Beast3 becoming more legible.

