I would focus on a few key areas.

⸻

1. normalization rules (critical)

Right now beast english is flexible. That is good for humans, but the system will need a strict internal form.

You already hinted at this.

Example:

make 2 image with red sky

should normalize to something like:

make image count 2 with red sky

or even:

action make
object image
count 2
style red sky

This layer is where:
	•	LLMs help
	•	C parser becomes deterministic
	•	commands become reproducible

If you do not define this early, drift will happen.

⸻

2. word expansion strategy (how you reach 666)

You have 66 words now. The next question is:

how do new words get added?

If this is loose, the language will decay.

You want rules like:
	•	new word must solve a real use case
	•	no synonyms if existing word works
	•	must not overlap meaning with existing word
	•	short preferred
	•	tested in real commands before inclusion

Also worth deciding:
	•	do you allow aliases, or enforce one canonical word?

My recommendation:
one canonical word, aliases only in input layer, not stored

⸻

3. command vs note vs doc separation

Right now you have three modes:
	•	command (make image)
	•	note (goal: fast gen)
	•	doc (academy text)

This is good, but worth formalizing.

Because later you may want:
	•	command parser (strict)
	•	note parser (semi-structured)
	•	doc parser (loose)

This ties directly into your pipeline:

input → interpretation → context → command → execution → artifact
￼

⸻

4. error language (very important for UX)

You already have:
	•	wtf
	•	glitch
	•	lgtm

But the system itself should also speak beast english.

Instead of:

error: insufficient memory

you might define:

unable to run
reason: low ram
need: more ram

This ties directly into your command philosophy:

systems should clearly execute or clearly refuse
￼

Designing this early will make the system feel consistent.

⸻

5. question forms (missing piece)

Commands are strong. Questions are still loose.

You will want patterns like:

why slow
what fail
how fix load
show best art

Define:
	•	question words (why what how when)
	•	expected response types

Otherwise LLM layer will stay fuzzy.

⸻

6. numbers and units

Right now you allow numbers, but not structure.

You should decide:

run gen 4 more
run gen 4
run gen count 4

All valid? Or normalize?

Also:
	•	time units (sec min hour day)
	•	size (mb gb)
	•	cost (optional later)

This becomes important for scheduling and mobile.

⸻

7. identity and reference system

Soon you will need:

run gen 42
show art 123
