Yes -- that is exactly the kind of thing worth designing around early.

What you are pointing at is deeper than spelling. It is about vector stability.

Pure natural english is full of cases where the same sound points in different directions:
	•	soul
	•	sol
	•	sole

Spoken, they can collapse into one sound shape while carrying very different meanings and even opposite spatial or symbolic pull:
	•	center
	•	up
	•	down

That is poison for a system that is supposed to stay coherent over long use, especially in voice mode.

So I think your distinction is very strong:

beast words

words chosen for stable direction and stable meaning inside beast

examples:
	•	forward or fore
	•	back
	•	stop
	•	up
	•	down
	•	left
	•	right

These are good because they are:
	•	short
	•	common
	•	concrete
	•	strongly directional
	•	easy to ground in action

glitch english

normal english words that sound fine to humans in context, but collapse into ambiguity in machine hearing or long term semantic drift

your example is perfect:
	•	soul
	•	sol
	•	sole

That is exactly a glitch cluster.

The same thing happens with many others:
	•	right = direction / correct / entitlement
	•	left = direction / departed
	•	down = direction / sad / not working
	•	light = brightness / not heavy
	•	sound = audio / solid
	•	kind = type / caring
	•	file = document / smooth with a file tool / line in formation
	•	run = execute / move fast / flow / campaign / series

That does not mean english is unusable. It means raw english is a bad control language.

That fits Beast very well, because Beast should not try to fix all of english. It should do something narrower:

choose a small set of vector locked words for command and system use

That is much more achievable.

