You’re zeroing in on the right constraint: sound → one canonical token, every time. The system should be boringly consistent, even if natural english is not.

voice to letter vs voice to syllable

"voice to letter" is viable if you mean:

map single phonetic units to a–z or 0–9 when the sound is unambiguous

It’s tighter than "syllable" and pushes you toward minimal tokens. The risk is over-collapsing multi-sound words. A clean compromise:
	•	voice to letter for single-letter utterances and spelled tokens
	•	voice to token for everything else (words like make, image, run)

So the pipeline becomes:

voice
-> voice to letter (when confident single letter)
-> voice to token (otherwise)
-> canonical beast text
-> parser

letter rule (your "be/bee" point)

Strongly agree with your rule. Make it explicit:

letter rule
	•	if spoken form matches a letter name with high confidence → emit the letter
	•	examples:

bee → b
be → b   (only when classified as letter, not verb)
see → c
tee → t
gee → g

The important part is the classifier:
	•	mode: letter (spelling / ids / short refs)
	•	mode: word (commands)

You decide the mode by context:
	•	after "spell", "id", "tag", or inside quotes → letter mode
	•	at sentence start with a verb slot → word mode

Examples:

spell b e a s t → b e a s t
tag g → g
make image → make image   (do not turn "make" into m a k e)

numbers (same principle)

two too to → 2   (only when used as quantity)
four fore for → 4   (only when used as quantity)

Guardrail:
	•	if token sits in a count slot → normalize to digit
	•	otherwise keep as word

"always shortest form" (good, with one guard)

Keep your rule:

always show the shortest canonical form

Add one guard:

only if confidence is high

If not, fall back to the safe word form and show a hint.

phonetic characters (do you need them?)

Your examples:
	•	ren-dez-vous
	•	nai-e-ve

This is useful, but be careful not to import full IPA complexity.

I would keep it lightweight and optional:

hyphen as phonetic separator

Use - to force segmentation when needed:

ren-dez-vous
nai-e-ve

Rules:
	•	hyphen splits tokens for pronunciation
	•	parser treats hyphenated word as one token
	•	only used when default mapping fails

minimal phonetic set (optional)

Only add characters if you hit real problems. If you do, keep it tiny:
	•	aa ee ii oo uu for long vowels (rare)
	•	sh ch th as digraphs (already common)

Avoid full phonetic alphabets. They will slow typing and break your "phone first" rule.

