⸻

1. define "unambiguous" (important)

Right now you say:

shortest unambiguous beast token

You should lock what that means.

Add:

unambiguous

a syllable is unambiguous when it maps to one canonical token in the beast phonetic dictionary

if multiple tokens are possible, choose the most common mapping or fall back to word rule

Why this matters:
	•	avoids hidden heuristics later
	•	keeps mapping deterministic

⸻

2. tie-breaking rule (edge cases)

What happens if two mappings are equally valid?

Example:
	•	"to" could be 2 or remain to

Add:

tie rule

if multiple valid mappings exist:
prefer single char token if confidence is high
otherwise keep phonetic word form

This prevents bad collapses in weak audio.

⸻

3. confidence threshold (quietly critical)

You do not want:

be → b

when the system only thinks it heard "be"

Add:

confidence rule

single char mapping requires high confidence in syllable detection

if confidence is low:
use phonetic word form

This will save you from a ton of real-world glitches.

⸻

4. gap normalization (very important for C)

Right now gaps are raw:

(.25s)
(.34s)

For parsing and storage, define buckets.

Add:

gap rule

gaps may be normalized into buckets:

short  < .2s
mid    .2s to .6s
long   > .6s

implementation may store exact time or bucketed form

This gives you:
	•	simpler parsing
	•	easier downstream logic

⸻

5. token boundary rule

Important for parser:

token rule

tokens are separated by space

hyphen is used only in timing artifact form

This keeps:

i c that u r

clean and easy.

⸻

