The UI shows a live stream of detected syllables, connected by hyphens:

i-c-that-u-r

or maybe:

4-ur-sol

The hyphens do not mean "word."
They mean:

these sounds arrived in one continuous utterance with only small gaps

That is a very good UI idea, because it lets the user verify:
	•	syllables were heard correctly
	•	they were not slurred together badly
	•	the mic did not lose a sound
	•	noise did not corrupt a chunk

It is basically a live low-level voice trace.

That feels much more honest than modern voice UIs, which jump too early to guessed text.

stage 2

delayed decode

After:
	•	a long silence, like 6 seconds
	•	or a trigger phrase, like execute command
	•	or manual confirmation

the system sends the syllable stream to an LLM with context and possible mappings.

That is strong, because the LLM is no longer doing raw ASR hallucination. It is doing:

constrained decode from known syllables

That is a far easier and cleaner problem.

your architecture is good

I would structure it like this:

audio
-> syllable detector
-> live hyphen ui
-> syllable artifact
-> stop condition
-> llm decode with context
-> beast command guess

And separately:

clear clear
-> wipe current syllable buffer

