the 6 second silence idea

Good default, but make it configurable.

You probably want:
	•	short pause: continue same utterance
	•	medium pause: maybe visual break
	•	long pause: send to decode

So maybe conceptually:
	•	under 0.5s: hyphen
	•	0.5s to 2s: minor break
	•	over 6s: decode trigger

Exact numbers can be tuned later.

"execute command" as a special sequence

Very good.

That gives users a deterministic way to end capture without waiting.

So:
	•	silence-based end
	•	phrase-based end
	•	maybe tap-based end

All three can coexist.

"clear clear"

Also strong.

It is short, memorable, and unlikely to be accidental in normal command speech.

I would define it as:

if clear clear is detected with high confidence, flush current live syllable buffer and cancel pending decode

That will feel good in practice.

sending syllables plus mapping dictionary to LLM

Yes -- and this is where your system gets much stronger than most existing voice interfaces.

Instead of giving the LLM noisy guessed text, give it:

1. syllable chain

Example:

i-c-that-u-r

2. possible mappings

Example:

i -> i
c -> see / sea / c
u -> you / u
r -> are / r
4 -> four / for / fore / 4

3. context

Examples:
	•	recent commands
	•	active mode
	•	current screen
	•	command vocabulary
	•	beast english dictionary

Then the LLM solves a constrained interpretation problem.

That is much better than standard voice pipelines that prematurely commit to one transcript.

very important design law

The LLM should receive:

the syllables as truth
the english expansion as hypothesis

Not the other way around.

That preserves the integrity of your architecture.

