You’re right to push on that. My earlier phrasing was sloppy.

In Beast, nothing semantic should happen before voice → canonical syllable tokens. So:

LLM decode and C decode are downstream. Always.

There is no "upstream normalization" in the sense of meaning or language. The only thing upstream of mapping is signal processing.

clean pipeline (corrected)

audio
→ signal processing (noise, gain)
→ syllable detection
→ syllable → canonical token mapping
→ voice trace (truth)
→ artifact stored

→ downstream decode:
    → beast decode (join)
    → english decode (split)
    → command execution (C)

So:
	•	voice to text (beast phonetics) = upstream
	•	LLM / C decode = downstream

⸻

what is upstream vs downstream

upstream (allowed before mapping)

purely mechanical:
	•	audio filtering
	•	silence detection
	•	syllable segmentation
	•	confidence scoring

These do not interpret meaning.

⸻

mapping layer (boundary)

syllable → token

This is the hard boundary.

After this point:
	•	you have canonical Beast input
	•	everything is stable and reproducible

⸻

downstream (all interpretation)

this includes:

1. beast decode (join)

i-c-u-r → i c u r

2. english decode (split / expand)

i-c-u-r → i see you are

3. command decode (C or LLM)

run-4-gen → execute generator 4 times

All of these are interpretation layers.

